# GitHub replies and comments from Cursor

When posting or suggesting **any** GitHub comment you draft in Cursor, the message must clearly indicate it came from Cursor. This includes:

- **PR conversation / timeline comments** (e.g. `gh pr comment`, REST `issues/{n}/comments` on a PR)
- **Review threads** and inline review replies
- **Issue comments** (non-PR issues)

Rules:

- Add a short footer on its own line after the substantive text, for example: `*Reply posted from Cursor.*` or `*— Drafted in Cursor.*`
- Do not skip the footer for “short” or “meta” PR comments (merge notes, cross-links to other PRs, etc.); those still count.

# Co-authored commits

When you propose or write a **full commit message** (not a one-line subject the user supplied verbatim) for work where Cursor or the agent **materially contributed** (logic, structure, or non-trivial text—not only applying an obvious user-specified edit), include a `Co-authored-by` trailer in the **commit message body**: one blank line after the subject line, then the trailer.

- Prefer the **exact** `Co-authored-by: …` line from the user’s Cursor **Settings → Agent → Commit attribution** when that feature is enabled (do not invent a different identity).
- If you have no access to that setting, use: `Co-authored-by: Cursor <noreply@cursor.com>` (the user may replace the email with whatever Cursor or their org standardizes on).
- Skip the trailer when the user clearly authored everything themselves and Cursor only ran commands or applied their exact instructions with no substantive generation.

# Pull request descriptions

When you draft or **substantially rewrite** a **pull request title or description** for GitHub, indicate Cursor involvement without burying the technical summary.

- Put a short disclosure **after** the main description, on its own line, for example: `*Drafted with Cursor.*` or `*PR description drafted with assistance from Cursor.*`
- If the PR body is mostly user-provided and you only tweak wording, you may use a lighter note (e.g. `*Minor edits with Cursor.*`) or omit if the change is trivial—use judgment.
